<section xml:id="c2s3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Minimum Spanning Tree</title>

   <definition xml:id="def-minSpanTree">
    <statement>
        <p>
            A <em>spanning tree</em> of a graph <m>G</m> is a subgraph of <m>G</m> that
             spans <m>G</m> (contains all nodes of <m>G</m>) and is a tree 
             (a connected, acyclic graph).
        </p>
    </statement>
   </definition>

   <p>
    Let <m>G</m> be a connected graph. Define a weight function: 
<md>
    <mrow>w: E(G) &amp; \rightarrow [0,\infty) </mrow>
  <mrow>e &amp; \mapsto w(e) </mrow>  
</md>

 </p>
 <p>
    Let <m>H</m> be a subgraph of <m>G</m>, then the weight of <m>H</m> is given 
    by <me>w(H)=\sum_{e\in H} w(e)</me>.
 </p>

<definition xml:id="def-">
    <statement>
        <p>
           A <em>minimum spanning tree</em> (MST) is a spanning tree for <m>G</m>
           which has minimum total weight. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>
 

    <p>
       <em> Minimum spanning tree problem </em> is a problem to find a spanning tree of <m>G</m> of minimum weight.
    </p>
<example>
    <p>
        In the graph <m>G</m> below, find a spanning tree of <m>G</m> of minimum weight. 
